description:
File: rust/lichen-node/src/node.rs:130-155

reply_echo_ipv6 accesses echo fields at fixed offsets without verifying the packet is long enough:

```rust
fn reply_echo_ipv6(&self, ipv6: &[u8], out: &mut [u8]) -> usize {
    // ... 
    let id_offset = icmpv6_start + echo_field::ID_OFFSET;
    let seq_offset = icmpv6_start + echo_field::SEQ_OFFSET;
    let data_offset = icmpv6_start + echo_field::DATA_OFFSET;

    let id = u16::from_be_bytes([ipv6[id_offset], ipv6[id_offset + 1]]);
    let seq = u16::from_be_bytes([ipv6[seq_offset], ipv6[seq_offset + 1]]);
    let data = &ipv6[data_offset..];
    // ...
}
```

While handle_ipv6 checks `n >= min_icmpv6_len`, this relies on ICMPV6_HEADER_LEN being >= 8. If the constant is wrong or changes, this could panic.

Impact: Low - ICMPV6_HEADER_LEN should always be 8, but defense in depth suggests explicit bounds checking.

Fix: Add explicit length check at the start of reply_echo_ipv6.
